WEBVTT

01:15.522 --> 01:19.168
Well, good morning, Concord and everybody online and all of our campuses as well.

01:19.188 --> 01:20.409
Just want to say hello to you.

01:20.449 --> 01:21.491
Glad you guys are here.

01:21.551 --> 01:25.217
If you got your word, turn to Mark chapter two is where we're going to be this morning.

01:25.697 --> 01:28.081
Mark chapter two versus one through 12.

01:28.862 --> 01:33.589
And so we're finishing up our series this morning entitled High Impact and it's been a three week series.

01:33.609 --> 01:39.999
So today's our final day for that and getting prepared for serve weekend next Saturday and Sunday.

01:40.079 --> 01:44.626
So Mark chapter two, one through 12, if you would, stand in honor of God's word as we read it together.

01:45.698 --> 01:45.898
All right.

01:45.918 --> 01:46.339
So here we go.

01:46.379 --> 01:46.880
Verse one.

01:46.900 --> 01:56.934
And when he returned to Capernaum, he being Jesus, after some days, it was reported that he was at home and many gathered together so that there was no more room, not even at the door.

01:57.515 --> 01:59.277
And he was preaching the word to them.

01:59.658 --> 02:03.703
And they came bringing to him a paralytic carried by four men.

02:04.224 --> 02:05.746
And when they could not get near

02:05.986 --> 02:16.961
to him because of the crowd, they removed the roof above him, and when they had made an opening, they let down the bed on which the paralytic lay, and when Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralytic son, your sins are forgiven.

02:17.041 --> 02:23.549
Now, some of the scribes that were sitting there questioning in their hearts, why does this man speak like that?

02:23.930 --> 02:25.091
He is blaspheming.

02:25.412 --> 02:27.595
Who can forgive sins but God?

02:27.975 --> 02:33.042
And immediately Jesus perceiving in his heart, or in his spirit, that they thus question within themselves,

02:33.154 --> 02:50.802
said to them why do you question these things in your heart which is easier to say to the paralytic your sins are forgiven or to say rise take up your bed and walk but that you may know that the son of man has authority on earth to forgive sins he said to the paralytic i say to you

02:50.882 --> 02:53.305
Rise, pick up your bed and go home.

02:53.666 --> 03:02.378
And he rose immediately and he picked up his bed and went out before them all so that they were all amazed and glorified God saying, we never saw anything like this.

03:02.739 --> 03:03.220
Let's pray.

03:03.680 --> 03:07.946
Father, help us to be astounded with how you work in our hearts.

03:08.507 --> 03:14.636
Thank God, thank you for this testimony that we see in Mark chapter two of how you worked and God, it's pointing to Jesus.

03:15.077 --> 03:16.018
Father, in his

03:16.162 --> 03:18.770
and who He is and what He can do in our lives.

03:18.810 --> 03:28.180
And so help us father to apply your word as we leave, that we would leave with the righteousness of Jesus produced in our hearts by the power of the Holy Spirit through your word.

03:28.340 --> 03:28.882
And we pray.

03:29.058 --> 03:29.498
Amen.

03:29.519 --> 03:30.840
You guys can have a seat.

03:30.860 --> 03:35.305
So high impact is our final message today as we move into next week.

03:35.425 --> 03:38.268
And so excited about this morning, excited about next weekend.

03:38.568 --> 03:41.452
Hope you guys are connected and ready to roll for next week.

03:41.672 --> 03:43.774
We don't want you to miss out on serve weekend.

03:43.814 --> 03:45.756
And I know some of you might not have signed up yet.

03:46.097 --> 03:48.940
And so come and see us out in the foyer of each of our campuses.

03:49.180 --> 03:50.682
You can also still sign up online.

03:50.702 --> 03:51.943
There's a couple of more projects.

03:51.983 --> 03:54.546
We would love to connect you to the weekend.

03:54.722 --> 03:58.909
So in prep for the weekend, we've always been talking about high impact.

03:58.949 --> 04:07.863
What can we do to have high impact, high amounts of influence in our society, in our culture, in our community that we live in here in the Northeast Georgia area?

04:07.883 --> 04:14.354
And I wanted to share with you a book, not necessarily read a book, but in 2000, there was a book that came out known as The Tipping Point.

04:14.775 --> 04:16.818
It was written by a guy named Malcolm Gladwell.

04:17.250 --> 04:19.874
And the premise of the book is a fascinating one.

04:19.894 --> 04:28.707
The artist and the book is a secular book about business and marketing and all of these other things, but really it also talks about sociology and psychology of who we are.

04:29.267 --> 04:39.442
And so in the book, Gladwell sets the stage for us to understand that there are certain ideas that begin to spread like an epidemic and then how those ideas

04:39.586 --> 04:44.093
end up taking form and taking shape and then also other people buying into those.

04:44.193 --> 04:52.506
And so he looks at market research, market analysis, people, psychology, sociology, and he comes up with this theory that there's this tipping point.

04:52.526 --> 04:54.389
And he says that the tipping point is 20%.

04:54.549 --> 05:05.746
And the 20% what it means is that somewhere in society, when you get to a point where 20% of the people have bought into the idea,

05:06.018 --> 05:16.692
Based upon his research that he did in order to write the book, he said that 20% then becomes the driving factor for the remaining 80% of the population or the group.

05:17.312 --> 05:25.643
In other words, he said, it's the point of critical mass where your idea goes from interesting to a few people to a must have for everyone.

05:25.683 --> 05:27.986
So for Gladwell, this 20%

05:28.098 --> 05:29.040
was the tipping point.

05:29.060 --> 05:32.024
And this really is not Gladwell's idea that he came up with.

05:32.085 --> 05:43.063
This is also known as the Pareto principle, where you've heard about the 2080 rule or the 8020 rule, and it's the idea that 20 really drive the thought and the action of the 80.

05:43.523 --> 05:52.498
And so you can see that all throughout the book, and it's built upon this idea that once you get the 20, you can eventually get to the 80.

05:53.026 --> 05:56.211
And so 20% is the tipping point, but I want to show you another stat today.

05:56.231 --> 05:58.334
And this is this one, 13.6%.

05:59.536 --> 06:03.883
And this stat is actually more representative of us in the room and us in our community.

06:03.903 --> 06:10.232
13.6% is the church membership to overall population where we live in the Northeast Georgia area.

06:10.253 --> 06:13.297
I got this from JoJo Thomas, who's our associational director for missions.

06:13.317 --> 06:19.026
Him and I were meeting earlier this week and actually talking about this stat and talking about also the tipping point.

06:19.394 --> 06:31.463
The idea that 20% once you can get to 20% of people, you have a better chance at reaching the remaining 80% of people when you've reached 20% of people because something happens at that 20%.

06:32.345 --> 06:35.954
But for us this morning, 13.6% is the important stat.

06:36.322 --> 06:46.433
Now, I know we can split hairs all day about church membership, like what is a church member and people from different denominations talk about that and how you quantify that and who becomes a church member.

06:46.453 --> 07:01.170
And we're not going to get into that this morning, but for the point of this, let's just assume that when we're saying church membership in our area, in our community, what we're talking about is people who have been baptized believers in Jesus Christ.

07:01.474 --> 07:07.047
So people who have pronounced faith in Jesus and then have become baptized and joined a church in this area.

07:07.628 --> 07:18.674
13.6 of the population that we live in are what we would say or have what we would say a reached a tipping point in their faith.

07:19.458 --> 07:39.662
So when we think about all these numbers, 13.6 and then also 228,000, that's the number of the people in our Northeast Georgia area and our five counties that don't have a church home that aren't connected, that haven't heard the gospel or if someone hasn't brought them to Jesus and they've answered in faith to Jesus like all these numbers, we start asking ourselves the question of like, how are we ever going to reach all of them?

07:41.164 --> 07:49.394
And you know, when we think about like our schools and our communities and our workplaces and the places that we know people are hanging out and living in our neighborhoods and we start

07:49.474 --> 07:59.674
adding up the number of people that don't know Jesus in our area, it is a daunting task to think about what we are called to do to make disciples in these, in this Northeast Georgia area.

07:59.694 --> 08:02.359
And so like, I'm just being a little honest here and transparent.

08:02.379 --> 08:11.858
When I see what we want to do and what we're called to do, I get a little anxious about it because that's, there's, there's, there's a lot at stake.

08:12.866 --> 08:31.484
But I think what's comforting and encouraging is what Jesus also gave us in Matthew chapter 28 in his great commission when he was telling us, go therefore and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and the Son and the Holy Spirit, teaching them to observe all that I have commanded you and behold, I am with you always.

08:33.085 --> 08:38.731
The goodness is that Jesus is with us as he has commissioned us.

08:41.073 --> 08:42.034
And so that,

08:43.426 --> 08:51.935
Coupled alongside of the fact that we are only at 13.6% really gets me fired up and gives me great hope.

08:53.517 --> 09:01.466
Because what Gladwell said was that when you get to 20% of a population or a group of people, then you have reached the tipping point.

09:01.486 --> 09:07.132
So I don't math well, but 13.6 is not very far from 20.

09:09.375 --> 09:12.338
So I don't know if you can see where I'm getting at, but we're only

09:12.514 --> 09:22.307
somewhere around like kinda 7%, 6% of reaching 20% of our population in this area with the gospel of Jesus Christ.

09:23.669 --> 09:30.178
We're only roughly 7% away from helping everyone in our area get to a tipping point in their faith.

09:30.218 --> 09:32.201
And I'm not saying that like this is automatic.

09:32.241 --> 09:42.194
I'm not saying that just because 20% by some guy that said it in a book or someone that wrote it and when we get to 20%, like everybody, the rest of the 80% is then going to turn to Jesus.

09:42.274 --> 09:52.040
I'm just saying that this doesn't seem as difficult as sometimes we make it out to seem or as the enemy wants to make us think that we're all at work.

09:52.121 --> 09:57.074
This is just all us by ourself because he is with us always.

09:58.178 --> 10:01.882
And so I don't think this morning we need a list of all the reasons that we're not sharing the gospel.

10:01.962 --> 10:05.325
I don't think we need a list of all the things that we're not doing in order to make disciples.

10:05.626 --> 10:14.235
I don't think we need to talk about all the things that we're not doing, even though those things are important, we need to overcome those things in the name of Jesus for the sake of the gospel and the glory of Jesus.

10:14.555 --> 10:16.557
I don't think we need to talk about all of those things.

10:16.737 --> 10:21.322
I just think we need to see that 13.6% is not that far away from 20%.

10:21.622 --> 10:25.106
And that would get us fired up to the stand

10:25.218 --> 10:36.862
from the standpoint that we would just think about 20% means that if each one of us would just look at the one in five people that we might know or have around us that don't know Jesus, one in five people is a start.

10:38.224 --> 10:42.994
Like if we could just help 20% of the people in our population.

10:43.426 --> 10:47.770
what I mean by our population, my personal population, my circle, my sphere of influence.

10:48.110 --> 10:52.414
If I could just help 20% of those people, that's just one, reach a tipping point in their faith.

10:52.855 --> 11:03.665
I am closer to reaching the 10, 20% in this Northeast Georgia community because when you start making disciples and you teach them to make disciples, it's not addition, it's multiplication.

11:05.967 --> 11:07.709
And so we're not far away.

11:09.391 --> 11:13.074
And because we're not far away, because 20% is not very far,

11:14.786 --> 11:20.253
For us this morning, instead of coming up with that list of things that we're not doing, let's look at the things that we can do.

11:21.815 --> 11:28.823
That we would do like the men in Mark chapter two, and we would stop seeing our obstacles and start going after opportunities.

11:30.005 --> 11:40.678
That we would stop seeing the obstacles that were in our way that would keep us from sharing the gospel, that would keep people from hearing the gospel, and we would start seeing the opportunities that we have to bring people before Jesus.

11:41.939 --> 11:44.082
And that's what the people in Mark chapter two did.

11:44.930 --> 11:49.795
And so the four friends in Mark chapter two, number one, they saw their opportunity despite their circumstances.

11:51.336 --> 11:57.182
Then amidst the circumstances that surrounded them, they saw an opportunity to bring their friend before Jesus.

11:57.262 --> 12:01.926
And so in verse one, and when he, he being Jesus, he returned to Capernaum.

12:01.966 --> 12:05.810
Capernaum was really a place for Jesus as a home baster in his Galilean ministry.

12:06.591 --> 12:08.112
And so he was in Capernaum hanging out.

12:08.212 --> 12:14.418
He was at home and he was there and it was reported that he was hanging out more than likely at Peter's house.

12:15.458 --> 12:20.948
And so in verse two, many were gathered together so that there was no more room.

12:21.109 --> 12:28.563
You guys ever been in a house where there was just no more room, maybe you're hanging out birthday party or maybe just with some friends or whatever.

12:28.603 --> 12:36.658
But I'm the kind of person, when you start walking around in the house and you can't go anywhere without touching someone, I just want to take a bath.

12:36.962 --> 12:37.983
It just kind of feels that way.

12:38.003 --> 12:42.149
And it probably felt that way then, you know, this nasty and hot and sweaty and dirty back then.

12:42.169 --> 12:48.638
And so there's no elbow room in the house so much so that like they were even out of the door, not even at the door was their room of the house.

12:49.720 --> 12:51.843
And he was preaching the word to them.

12:51.923 --> 12:55.788
Now the word is important because we need to see that because it's going to come into play later.

12:55.828 --> 13:00.895
But the word that it's referring to is the good news of the gospel of Jesus Christ.

13:00.915 --> 13:05.842
It's the good news that the kingdom of God is now at hand in the personal ministry of Jesus.

13:06.658 --> 13:08.642
That was the word that he was proclaiming.

13:09.865 --> 13:11.488
And so yes, Jesus healed people.

13:11.849 --> 13:14.193
Yes, he ministered to people.

13:14.214 --> 13:19.544
Yes, he spent time with people that were marginalized and ostracized from society.

13:19.565 --> 13:28.082
He spent time with those folks, but more than anything, Jesus was about the word, the word, the good news of the gospel of Jesus Christ.

13:29.282 --> 13:33.688
And so that's what we need to be about as well as we are going out in our communities this next weekend.

13:33.708 --> 13:40.878
Each and every day as we live, like we meet needs, yes, but more importantly, we need to make sure that our good works don't cover up our good words.

13:43.442 --> 13:52.734
And so Jesus was preaching the word to them and then they came, they being a group of four men bringing to him a paralytic.

13:52.754 --> 13:54.357
So these four guys had a friend.

13:54.377 --> 13:55.718
Here's their set of circumstances.

13:55.779 --> 13:58.322
We've got this friend who's in need

13:58.562 --> 14:00.905
of Jesus who's in need of healing.

14:01.186 --> 14:04.271
He needs something and only that guy has it.

14:06.173 --> 14:09.799
And so their circumstances is they have a friend who is in brokenness.

14:11.021 --> 14:19.513
And so for us in our area and personally, like what are some circumstances in your life and our life and our area and our community that need Jesus?

14:20.915 --> 14:22.738
What are areas in your life personally?

14:23.234 --> 14:25.676
What are areas in the lives of those of people around us?

14:25.756 --> 14:27.478
What is the need of those around us?

14:27.638 --> 14:28.939
The brokenness around us.

14:29.440 --> 14:31.882
Where does Jesus need to be?

14:32.002 --> 14:34.565
Or who do we need to bring to Jesus?

14:34.605 --> 14:36.487
What are the set of circumstances that exist?

14:36.507 --> 14:38.328
How many broken homes are in our area?

14:38.348 --> 14:39.870
How many children need our help?

14:40.070 --> 14:41.812
How many people need to hear the gospel?

14:42.012 --> 14:45.796
All of those circumstances create for us an opportunity, not an obstacle.

14:47.797 --> 14:52.562
Brokenness is just an opportunity for the gospel to speak into and for it to heal it.

14:53.442 --> 14:55.785
And so these four men saw brokenness in their friend.

14:57.527 --> 15:00.350
And so in the midst of those circumstances, they saw opportunity.

15:00.370 --> 15:01.331
They didn't see obstacle.

15:01.351 --> 15:03.674
They were like, he needs something that that guy has.

15:04.015 --> 15:04.856
Let's get him to them.

15:04.916 --> 15:08.760
And so then number two, they seized an opportunity to be creative.

15:10.302 --> 15:20.274
So they saw an opportunity amidst their circumstances, but then they seized an opportunity to be creative and in verse three, they came bringing to him a paralytic carried by four

15:20.354 --> 15:20.735
men.

15:20.755 --> 15:24.682
So four guys carrying the paralytic probably on some kind of stretcher or mad.

15:24.702 --> 15:29.852
We're not really sure what it would have looked like, but you know, you can get the idea of how you would carry someone for people at a time.

15:30.173 --> 15:37.106
And when they could not get near to him in the house because of the crowd, remember it was packed, they removed the roof above him.

15:37.666 --> 15:42.953
So more than likely that one of the obstacles that was in the way of these guys was like, we gotta get to Jesus.

15:43.013 --> 15:43.894
We can't get through the house.

15:43.974 --> 15:44.855
Now we gotta get up the roof.

15:44.875 --> 15:45.596
That's an obstacle.

15:46.177 --> 15:46.818
So what do we do?

15:46.918 --> 15:48.880
That's our circumstance, present at the moment.

15:48.900 --> 15:49.781
Well, let's be creative.

15:49.802 --> 15:51.444
Let's get him up on top of the roof.

15:51.544 --> 15:55.389
And if, I don't know if I'm paralytic and I'm sitting there and I'm on the bed listening to this happen.

15:55.409 --> 15:58.553
Like I know I wanna be healed, but like my four friends said, hey, it's crowded.

15:58.573 --> 15:59.534
We're gonna take you on the roof.

15:59.614 --> 16:00.856
I'm like, I vote no, you know?

16:02.538 --> 16:05.842
And really like we're going into serve weekend on Saturday.

16:05.922 --> 16:09.026
The next part is like what we don't need to do to get people to Jesus.

16:09.086 --> 16:12.090
Please don't tear a hole in a roof this week to get Jesus to people, okay?

16:12.410 --> 16:21.823
But what they did, they got up on the roof and when they made an opening, they then let him down on the bed of which the paralytic lay.

16:21.883 --> 16:23.665
Notice the creativity that these guys have.

16:25.087 --> 16:33.458
I mean, how many of us sometimes, when we see the need that's around us, the circumstances that are in front of us, of which we can share the gospel with, then we really start seeing the obstacles too.

16:34.146 --> 16:39.675
And instead of focusing on the opportunity, we start focusing on the obstacles and the obstacles cause us to go.

16:40.477 --> 16:41.018
And you know what?

16:41.038 --> 16:43.222
That's kind of difficult and we're going to turn around and walk away.

16:43.262 --> 16:43.662
You know what?

16:43.863 --> 16:45.045
That's going to be a little awkward.

16:45.065 --> 16:46.507
Let me turn around and walk away from that.

16:46.527 --> 16:47.729
That's going to be a little bit messy.

16:47.749 --> 16:48.851
I might have to work on that.

16:49.092 --> 16:50.815
Let's turn around and walk away from that.

16:50.835 --> 16:58.608
Those four guys could have easily walked away from that situation saying, hey, maybe another day, but they looked at it and they said, you know what?

16:58.628 --> 16:59.890
Let's get creative about it.

17:00.738 --> 17:05.884
Let's carry him up on the roof and let's get him to the roof and let's dig a hole in the roof and then let's let him down.

17:07.826 --> 17:11.710
Have you ever been creative to get someone in front of Jesus?

17:11.730 --> 17:21.541
Have you ever had an experience where you've had to go a little bit outside of the norm or maybe this morning you're feeling guilty because you're like, I'm not being really creative at all to like bring people to Jesus.

17:21.561 --> 17:23.243
I'm not bringing people to Jesus at all.

17:23.263 --> 17:29.810
Well, then let's back it up a little bit and let's just start at maybe being creative is just inviting someone into your home.

17:31.170 --> 17:37.416
Like you don't have to create a club, you don't have to create a study, you don't have to create a 12-step program for how you're going to reach people.

17:37.676 --> 17:43.282
Like maybe you just need to start practicing gospel hospitality and just opening up your home to somebody that doesn't know Jesus.

17:45.404 --> 17:52.390
It doesn't have to be perfect, it doesn't have to be all put together, it doesn't have to look neat and clean, but just inviting them over.

17:53.512 --> 18:00.178
Or maybe creativity means taking someone to lunch or taking lunch with someone different than what you normally do in your place of work.

18:00.418 --> 18:02.101
going to lunch with a different group of people.

18:02.802 --> 18:04.284
I know school's about to start back.

18:04.765 --> 18:06.227
Maybe it's sitting at a different table.

18:07.629 --> 18:11.255
Maybe it's being around people that are a little bit more unique than you are.

18:13.358 --> 18:17.524
Maybe creativity doesn't have to be this grand thing like carrying someone on a roof and tearing a hole.

18:17.564 --> 18:21.150
Maybe it just needs to start with being in a different place than you were before.

18:21.490 --> 18:24.495
Or maybe it's just going out of your way to serve someone like we're doing this weekend.

18:24.996 --> 18:26.418
Or like you can do each and every day.

18:27.906 --> 18:30.630
And so are we being creative in how we bring people to Jesus?

18:30.670 --> 18:43.390
Because when we see our circumstances, not as obstacles, but as opportunities, we will then begin thinking and praying about Lord, give us these opportunities and we will start seeing how to be creative to bring people to Jesus.

18:43.470 --> 18:51.202
And notice that when we begin doing that, we begin putting ourselves in a position where we can watch Jesus work.

18:52.324 --> 18:53.706
We're not the heroes in the story.

18:54.868 --> 18:56.370
Jesus is the hero in the story.

18:57.378 --> 19:01.103
And so in Mark chapter two, Jesus took an opportunity to heal the man's condition.

19:02.384 --> 19:07.611
So the four friends, they brought the friend to Jesus, they didn't see obstacles, they saw opportunity and they got creative how to get him there.

19:07.631 --> 19:09.754
And once they got him there, Jesus healed the man's condition.

19:09.774 --> 19:19.186
Verse six, now some of the scribes, sorry, verse five, when Jesus saw their faith, so they lowered him down into the room where Jesus was,

19:19.298 --> 19:27.747
And it says, when Jesus saw their faith, there being the group of guys, not just the paralytic, but the four friends, all of them collectively together, especially the guy that was on the mat.

19:27.767 --> 19:31.191
It takes faith to get lowered through a roof on a stretcher by four friends, right?

19:31.391 --> 19:31.651
Okay.

19:32.812 --> 19:39.800
So when they saw their faith, now don't miss the fact that what their faith was predicated upon.

19:41.181 --> 19:45.906
It was predicated upon what they were already experiencing at the house, and that was the preaching of the word.

19:46.786 --> 19:53.815
So the good news, the proclamation of the good news of the kingdom of God, that Jesus' ministry has now bringing forth the kingdom of God.

19:54.176 --> 19:59.583
They were hearing that and had somewhere experienced that, maybe through someone else, and they heard about this guy.

19:59.964 --> 20:08.756
And because of their faith in Jesus, Jesus says to the man because of his faith, son, your sins are forgiven.

20:09.256 --> 20:10.578
He got at the heart of the issue.

20:12.866 --> 20:17.234
It wasn't that yes, this man needed healing, but more than healing, he needed ultimate healing.

20:19.338 --> 20:21.382
He had now trusted and put faith in Jesus.

20:21.482 --> 20:23.987
And so Jesus was going to heal the man ultimately.

20:25.830 --> 20:28.235
And so he speaks forgiveness over the man.

20:29.858 --> 20:32.082
And then that is why we bring people to Jesus.

20:32.386 --> 20:35.549
We bring people to Jesus so that they can experience ultimate healing.

20:35.569 --> 20:36.630
We bring people to Jesus.

20:36.670 --> 20:37.591
We're creative about it.

20:37.631 --> 20:45.739
We see opportunities in our obstacles because we know that the one thing that Jesus can do for them is the one thing that we can't and that's forgive sins.

20:47.321 --> 20:52.145
And so now some of the scribes were sitting there and they were questioning in their hearts.

